This paper discusses the use of variational autoencoders for approximate inference, which is a common topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence research. The paper specifically focuses on the factors that affect the quality of posterior inference in these models, which suggests that it may be relevant to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE), and systems and control (cs.SY). Among these, cs.LG is the most likely sub-category, as it is the most general and encompasses a wide range of topics related to machine learning and statistical inference. The other sub-categories are also relevant, as they all involve some aspect of machine learning or artificial intelligence, but they may be less likely because they are more specific and may not cover all aspects of the paper's content.
